That said, there are a few things I really think could make it better. First off, for a game that‚Äôs all about collecting awesome loot, it‚Äôs kind of a bummer that none of the gear shows up on your character. Like, I‚Äôd love to actually see the helmets, gloves, boots, and chest pieces I‚Äôm equipping. Right now, your character just has the default look no matter what. In 2025, that‚Äôs just not cutting it ‚Äî especially when other, lower-budget games are doing this already.

Also, since co-op is a big part of the game, it‚Äôd be awesome to have some weapons or items that actually work together. Imagine if there was an electricity item that could connect between two players‚Äô drops, or fire grenades that could combine effects ‚Äî stuff like that would make teamwork way more fun and rewarding.

Overall, I like where this is going, but there‚Äôs definitely room for some cool upgrades.

The game opens with a strong set of visuals and story premise. The tutorial feels well integrated, but I was left wondering what this astronaut‚Äôs deal was. We don‚Äôt know where she was going or why. We have an objective-escape the planet- but I find it unusual that the astronaut‚Äôs first goal isn‚Äôt to get in touch with someone else about her crash- does she have no oversight? That would be fine for a solo explorer, except for a small tidbit of info dropped at the very end of the game. It feels like things just don‚Äôt add up.

The environments are very well realized for this type of adventure game, and very thoughtful in their functionality for mobile. I do wish the various creatures were better realized; at first, I felt like they must ‚Äúactually‚Äù look like that on this strange planet. However, another reveal later in the game defies this idea and highlights that these silhouetted creatures definitely aren‚Äôt well thought out in terms of design.

The puzzles were reasonable; for better or worse, the days of sitting stuck on a tough puzzler for weeks to months without a walkthrough or guide are gone. Mobile does tend to make puzzling a little less robust- the types of puzzles begin to feel a bit repetitive by the end of the game. That said, they did feel well integrated into the world that was crafted.

However, the character lines around the puzzles really cheapens the experience. I don‚Äôt want to feel like I‚Äôm being led around by the nose or that I‚Äôm listening to a kid‚Äôs TV show. Several times I wondered if this game was directed at kindergarteners because of the tone the astronaut was using. Still, I appreciate that the character is voice acted at all- full V.O.‚Äôs can be somewhat rare in the genre.

Our astronaut is also very curious about the planet, but is adamant that she‚Äôs getting out of there ASAP. Isn‚Äôt she an explorer? well, here‚Äôs a chance to explore! More than once we also end up relying on her gut feelings, adding to how contrived the short story line feels.

The reveal in Act 5 is pretty cool; I didn‚Äôt know what to expect about the fate of the planet, but it wasn‚Äôt that. Unfortunately, the end of the game really leaves a lot to be desired. Apparently this game connects to something else the developer has done, but it wasn‚Äôt clear that you needed that knowledge ahead of time to make the ending feel exciting. It‚Äôs also possible that this game will get a sequel, but if it doesn‚Äôt, there are so many unanswered questions created by the ending that it feels incredibly unsatisfying. I did not expect to end this game feeling very sad about the outcome for the astronaut and other environments/creatures/etc, but that‚Äôs where I‚Äôm at.

Final thing:  the musical sting used in cut scenes is really great! But it gets old fast. A little more variety would have been nice. 

Overall okay. I‚Äôd add a half star if I could just to support the work that went into all the art, but I just think the story isn‚Äôt tight enough to support the experience this game needed to really make a splash.
